Comment: A combination of some very poor chess and some very tricky tactics, but in the end it came together surprisingly. I am black playing at the time an opponent of very similar chessic knowledge. E4
C5 the sicilian defence, i like the sicilian because i always like to develop away from the centre and counter attack later on

d4, an aggressive leap. White generally wants to have no options for black to extend its pawns to the centre. I personally dont mind this as this system doesnt require such a dominant presence in the centre
d6 keeps my presence there but nothing forcing.
d5 closing the space, stopping my queen knight on the c6 square. Its annoying for black, but at the moment I didnt really mind this otherwise i would of probably taken on d4
nf6, attacking both. developing a piece. Nothing more complex than that
f3 defending
i played e6 to again open up for development, counter and trying to pursue white to give up his nice centre
he exchanges pawns allowing me to develop my bishop, the centre i feel now is mine.
he exchanges pawns allowing me to develop my bishop, the centre i feel now is mine.
simple bishop check
i gave up my knight in the hope he will give up his light square bishop to make mine strong. My knight isnt really doing anything in this position.
my pawns are doubled. doubled pawns arent always bad. The double pawns sort of cement my presence in the centre allowing any attack to undouble my pawns and obtain a dominant pawn island

i really like this move, d4 shuts down that bishop. This move i feel played a huge part in my victory. I always had the idea that his dark squared bishop would be a weakness as my centre is much stronger and the influence of the piece is very limited. As you notice the game develop keep and eye on d4
